nt (non-dopplerable); PT pulse dopplerable. Findings are consistent with severe arterial disease and unchanged from baseline.\n- Physical Examination (Wounds): New left 2nd toe ulceration; left 1st hallux blister with drainage; chronic non-healing left 4th toe ulcer; new right 4th toe ulceration. Groin access site post-procedure was clean, dry, and intact without hematoma.\n- Bilateral Lower Extremity Angiogram: Findings revealed multi-segmental arterial disease including total occlusion of the left superficial femoral artery (SFA), the previous left femoral-to-posterior tibial bypass graft, and the left popliteal artery. Additionally, the right SFA and right popliteal artery were occluded.\n- Clinical Course: Diagnostic mapping confirmed the need for revascularization. The patient is scheduled for a planned readmission for a redo left femoral-to-posterior tibial bypass. Lisinopril and Rivaroxaban were held pending surgery.",
